      "id": "switch-intro",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## 5. The `switch` Statement\n\nWhen you have many specific values to check (not ranges), `switch` can be cleaner than many `if-else-if` statements.\n\n### Syntax:\n```java\nswitch (variable) {\n    case value1:\n        // code for value1\n        break;\n    case value2:\n        // code for value2\n        break;\n    case value3:\n        // code for value3\n        break;\n    default:\n        // code if no case matches\n}\n```\n\n### Important:\n- The `break` statement exits the switch. Without it, execution \"falls through\" to the next case.\n- `default` is like `else` - it runs if no case matches (optional but recommended).\n- Switch works with: `byte`, `short`, `int`, `char`, `String`, and enums.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "switch-intro"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "switch-example",
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "// Day of the week\nint dayNumber = 3;\nString dayName;\n\nswitch (dayNumber) {\n    case 1:\n        dayName = \"Monday\";\n        break;\n    case 2:\n        dayName = \"Tuesday\";\n        break;\n    case 3:\n        dayName = \"Wednesday\";\n        break;\n    case 4:\n        dayName = \"Thursday\";\n        break;\n    case 5:\n        dayName = \"Friday\";\n        break;\n    case 6:\n        dayName = \"Saturday\";\n        break;\n    case 7:\n        dayName = \"Sunday\";\n        break;\n    default:\n        dayName = \"Invalid day\";\n}\n\nSystem.out.println(\"Day \" + dayNumber + \" is \" + dayName);",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "java"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
